"Pap J., Frölich C., Kuhn J., Sofia S., Ulrich R.","A discussion of recent evidence for solar irradiance variability and climate",2002,"Advances in Space Research","29","10",,"1417","1426",,,10.1016/S0273-1177(02)00206-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0036577874&partnerID=40&md5=c4ecfe70db2ab00ccfbeecb3fbcf7df0","University of California, 405 Hilgard Ave., Los Angeles, CA 90095-1562, United States","Pap, J., University of California, 405 Hilgard Ave., Los Angeles, CA 90095-1562, United States; Frölich, C., University of California, 405 Hilgard Ave., Los Angeles, CA 90095-1562, United States; Kuhn, J., University of California, 405 Hilgard Ave., Los Angeles, CA 90095-1562, United States; Sofia, S., University of California, 405 Hilgard Ave., Los Angeles, CA 90095-1562, United States; Ulrich, R., University of California, 405 Hilgard Ave., Los Angeles, CA 90095-1562, United States","One of the over-arching questions, among others, to be addressed by studying Sun-Earth connections is: ""Is the climate changing in a way we can understand and predict?"" The Earth's climate is the result of a complex and incompletely understood system of external inputs and interacting parts. Climate change can occur over a range of time scales, may be driven by natural variability, including solar variability, and/or anthropogenic causes and may be identified through the study of a variety of measurable parameters. Global climate change in response to human influences is one of the pressing threats facing science today. However, many of the external factors that govern our climate, including solar variability, cannot be adequately determined from existing operational observations. Since the Sun is the fundamental source of energy that sustains life on Earth, establishing its radiation environment, controls its temperature and atmospheric composition, the accurate knowledge of the solar radiation received by the Earth and understanding of its variability are critical for environmental science and climate studies. In this paper we point out the necessity of a new strategy, i.e., to study global solar properties, such as solar irradiance, solar shape, shape oscillations, and radius, to better understand the origin of solar-induced climate changes. © 2002 COSPAR. Published by Elsevier Science Ltd. All rights reserved.",,"Atmospheric composition; Atmospheric temperature; Climate change; Irradiation; Solar shape; Space research; climate change; irradiance; solar radiation",,,,,,"Bradley, R.S., Jones, P.D., (1993) The Holocene, 3 (4), p. 367; Brown, T., (1987) Solar Radiative Output Variations, , edited by P. Foukal, NCAR, Boulder; Chapman, G.A., Cookson, A.M., Dobias, J.J., (1996) J. Geophys. Res, 101, p. 13541; Crowley, T.J., Kim, K.-Y., (1996) G. Res. L, 23 (4), p. 359; Delache, Ph., Lacrare, F., Sadsaoud, H., (1986) Advance in Helio- and Asteroseismology, p. 223. , edited by J. Christensen-Dalsgaard, S. Frandsen, IAU Press; Eddy, J.A., (1977) Climatic Change, 1, p. 173; Foukal, P., Lean, J., (1988) ApJ, 328, p. 347; Fox, P., Sofia, S., Chan, K.L., (1991) Solar Phys, 135, p. 15; Fox, P., Sofia, S., (1994) The Sun as a Variable Star: Solar and Stellar Irradiance Variations, p. 280. , (eds.: J.M. Pap, C. Fröhlich, H.S. Hudson, S. Solanki), Cambridge Univ. Press; Friis-Christensen, E., Lassen, K., (1991) Science, 254, p. 698; Fröhlich, C., (1977) Solar Output and Its Variation, p. 93. , edited by O.R. White, Univ. Colorado Press; Fröhlich, C., Pap, J., (1989) Astron. Astrophys, 220, p. 272; Fröhlich, (1997) Solar Physics, 170, p. 1; Fröhlich, C., (1998) Solar Electromagnetic Radiation Study fo Solar Cycle 22, p. 391. , edited by J.M. Pap, C. Fröhlich, R. Ulrich, Kluwer Academic Publishers; Fröhlich, C., Lean, J., (1998) Proceedings of the IAU Symposium, 185, p. 89. , edited by F.L. Deubner, Kluwer Academic Publishers; Fröhlich, C., (2000) Space Science Reviews, 94, p. 15; Hansen, (1981) Science, 213, p. 957; Hansen, J., Lacis, A., (19